6-Wks Post-Op.bscp_comments: A2CPS Coordinator was practicing blood draws for her studies and to be able to perform blood draws. When she asked the pt which arm, pt said left. A2CPS RC got a pillow and placed it under her arm. She wiped off the are with alcohol swab, and placed tourniquet on. She connected the adapters and began extracting the blood. A2CPS RC asked me what I would do? I was confused and when I looked, I saw the adapter came apart. The needle with the gray covering was stuck in the vacu tube, and that part was on the ground. Blood was leaking over the pillow, floor, and table. A2CPS coordinator placed gauze on need, removed tourniquet and wrapped her arm. Both of us worked on cleaning up the blood spill, and once everything was contained, we got a new set of supplies (minus the pax gene and LAV tubes). A2CPS RC was able to draw from right arm, and pt was walked out  by me. She was fine. I talked with Kathy to become informed of steps to cleaning a blood spill in an exam room opposed to having one in our lab. Centrifuge start time was 10:24am since both coordinators were cleaning up spill, ensuring pt was tended to.
